The write-down of European debt is inevitable
Berkeley — — "That was just the Greek crisis," "That was just the crisis of Greece and Ireland," people used to think, but now it's not possible, because it's obviously become a crisis of the eurozone.
Dealing with it is both easier and more difficult than usually anticipated.
The economics of this crisis is quite simple.
Greece has fiscal problems.
Ireland's banking sector is problematic.
Portugal's private debt market is problematic.
Spain has problems in all of the above three areas.
Although the details differ, the conclusion is the same: these countries all have to undergo a painful process of spending cuts.
To offset the side effects of austerity policies, the usual approach is to combine domestic spending cuts with currency depreciation.
Devaluation enhances export competitiveness, which means using external demand to compensate for internal demand.
However, these countries are all eurozone countries, which do not have an independent currency to devalue, so they can only use internal devaluation as a substitute for external devaluation.
They must cut wages, pensions, and other costs to increase export competitiveness and achieve the effect of expanding external demand.
In fact, these crisis countries have made considerable efforts to tighten their belts.
But there is one economic variable that has not changed along with the adjustments of other variables, which is the level of debt in the public and private sectors.
The face value of government accumulated debt has not changed, and bank debt — except for some debt owed to junior creditors — has also remained largely unchanged.
This simple fact puts the internal devaluation strategy into a paradox: the more wages and other costs are cut, the heavier the relative burden of accumulated debt becomes.
The heavier the debt burden, the more public spending must be cut and taxes increased to meet the debt obligations of the government and its protectors (such as banks).
This in turn requires more internal devaluation, further increasing the debt burden, creating a vicious cycle that drags the economy into a depression.
Therefore, for the internal devaluation strategy to work, it is necessary to find ways to reduce the face value of debt.
Government debt must be restructured.
Bank debt must be converted into equity, and mortgage debt should be written down when banks are insolvent.
Mortgage debt must also be reduced.
It is understandable that policymakers are reluctant to take this path.
Contracts are sacred.
The government is worried about losing credibility in financial markets.
If creditors are mainly from abroad, especially foreign banks, write-downs would only hurt other countries.
These concerns are not entirely unfounded, but they should not lead to unreasonable conclusions.
The only two options are internal devaluation or external devaluation.
European country leaders must choose one of the two.
They all ruled out the path of external devaluation.
But internal devaluation necessarily requires debt restructuring.
Denying this is both illogical and unreasonable.
Debt restructuring is straightforward to implement.
The government can issue a batch of bonds with a face value discounted by a certain proportion of the current debt face value.
Bondholders can choose between two options: either hold onto their bonds and redeem them at face value when they mature, which will be later but with a lower interest rate; or accept discounted bonds with a lower face value, which will mature earlier but with a higher interest rate.
This is not some cutting-edge technology; people have done this before.
But to make it work, there are three prerequisites.
The first is to assure bondholders of the safety of the new bonds.
Someone has to guarantee this batch of bonds.
In the 1980s, during the debt restructuring in Latin America under the Brady plan, the U.S. Treasury played the role of "guarantor leader."
Now, the International Monetary Fund and the German government can take on this responsibility.
Second, all countries must act in unison.
Otherwise, a country's restructuring will raise expectations for other countries, causing contagion effects.
Finally, the banks that suffer losses from debt restructuring must have their balance sheets strengthened.
These banks need to undergo real stress tests, not the token exercise that was done earlier this year.
If debt restructuring implies capital shortfalls, a comprehensive debt-for-equity swap must be carried out on the relevant banks' assets.
If that is not enough, the government must inject capital into the relevant banks.
This also requires consistent action across all countries.
Once the banks' balance sheets are stabilized, it may be possible to restructure mortgage debt, bank debt, and other private sector debts without destabilizing the entire financial system.
Now let's talk about the biggest challenge.
All of this requires resolute leadership.
German leaders must acknowledge that their country's banks face significant exposure to debt in peripheral eurozone countries, and the situation is urgent.
They must convince backroom bosses and voters that using public funds to guarantee debt restructuring and bank recapitalization is a necessary part of an internal devaluation strategy; since Germany is urging other EU countries to adopt this strategy, it should毫不犹豫ly take on the responsibility of providing guarantees.
In short, European leaders, especially German leaders, need to make the consequences sound more severe — — without doing so, there will be major trouble.
Because that is the reality.
